[2] Canada (Ontario)
Date: 25 Mar 2014
Source: CBC [edited]
http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/ottawa/measles-in-ottawa-up-to-4-confirmed-cases-1.2585723


Two more cases of measles have been confirmed in Ottawa, Ottawa Public Health (OPH) announced Tuesday [25 Mar 2014]. In a news release, OPH said one immunized adult and one unimmunized child contracted the virus from contact with a previous case.

Symptoms of measles may develop 7 to 21 days after exposure to an infected person. Symptoms include a high fever, runny nose, cough, drowsiness, irritability and red eyes. Small white spots may appear in the mouth and throat. A red blotchy rash begins to appear on the face 3 to 7 days after the start of symptoms then spreads down the body to the arms and legs. This rash usually lasts 4 to 7 days. Symptoms generally last from 1-2 weeks (source: Ottawa Public Health). They said these 3rd and 4th diagnoses since 5 Mar 2014 are not unexpected because virtually everyone who comes into contact with the virus and is not immune will become infected.

OPH said people at the following locations and times should have checked with their healthcare providers if they were unsure about their immunization status:

18 Mar 2014 from 9 a.m. to 6:30 p.m.: Businesses at 411 Legget Drive.
18 Mar 2014 from 1:15 p.m. to 3:30 p.m.: Subway restaurant at 700 March Road.
20 Mar 2014, 6 p.m. to 8:40 p.m.: Shoppers Drug Mart at 1300 Stittsville, Main Street.
21 Mar 2014, 6:30 a.m. to 10 a.m.: Nepean Sportsplex at 1701 Woodroffe Avenue.
21 Mar 2014, 11:30 a.m. to 2 p.m.: Quizno's Restaurant at 4048 Carling Avenue.
21 Mar 2014, 9 a.m. to 5:30 p.m.: Businesses at 411 Legget Drive.

If you are unimmunized, have a weakened immune system, are pregnant, are a worker in the child or health care sector, or had a child under age one with you when you visited one of these locations during the times above, you're asked to contact Ottawa Public Health at 613-580-6744.

Ottawa's 1st confirmed case of measles in 3 years was announced on 5 Mar 2014 when an unimmunized child returned from the Philippines. Measles can lead to ear infections, pneumonia, swelling of the brain and even death, and is more severe in adults and infants.

