[5] USA (California)
Date: 27 Mar 2014
Source: KPHO [edited]
http://www.kpho.com/story/25088306/measles-outbreak-hits-so-california


Measles, an extremely contagious disease, is quickly spreading in parts of California, as dozens of cases have already been reported.

"It starts with a fever, a runny nose, and a dry cough and red eyes. Usually, after around 3 or 4 days into it, [people] characteristically get this red, bumpy rash that starts at the forehead and ears and just goes down the body," the San Diego Health Department's Dr. Eric McDonald said.

There are 47 cases of measles in the state. San Diego's neighbor to the north, Orange County [OC], has nearly half of them. "They're our neighbors, and diseases don't respect geographic boundaries," Dr. McDonald said.

The San Diego Health Department says some of those infected in OC exposed people in San Diego. Investigators had to make sure the disease hadn't spread. San Diego had 4 cases of its own from one person who flew in from out of the country. "We need to reach out and contact well over 1000 people, and give them the information that they were exposed, and also find out if they were at risk," Dr. McDonald said.

All the concern is because measles is so contagious that someone can be exposed [up to] an hour after an infected person leaves the room. "This is one of the most contagious diseases that we know about," Dr. McDonald said.

Public health officials measure the spread of an infectious disease with something called R-naught. For the flu, every person who is sick is expected to infect one [or] 2 people. For measles, every person who's infected can sicken 17 to 20 if they're not vaccinated.

Cases are widespread in certain regions of the word, including Africa, Asia and the Philippines. San Diego health officials are putting up flyers to warn people who travel to those areas to make sure they're vaccinated.

"I only realized it after 3 years staying here in America that I need to have those shots once I go back to the Philippines," one man said.
The man said, after his wife contracted measles in the Philippines, that it is a disease he wouldn't want to get. "I always call my insurance agency [to see] if there's any vaccination that I need to have before going to the Philippines," he said.

--
