[7] USA (Washington)
Date: 28 Mar 2014
Source: The Bellingham Herald [edited]
http://www.bellinghamherald.com/2014/03/28/3557771/one-whatcom-county-resident-contracted.html


A Whatcom County resident is among those who contracted measles in an outbreak that began earlier this month [March 2014] in the Fraser Valley in British Columbia.

The number of confirmed cases in the Fraser Valley East communities -- Abbotsford, Mission, Chilliwack, Agassiz, Harrison Hot Springs, and Hope -- totaled 237 as of Wed 26 Mar 2014, according to B.C. public health officials.

Officials there declared an outbreak on 8 Mar 2014. Most of the cases were related to a private school with a high number of unvaccinated children, and the outbreak hasn't spread much beyond the Fraser Valley East communities.

The county resident who contracted measles has ties to the school, according to the Whatcom County Health Department. The person has been isolated and is being watched.

"The general public is not at risk," said Dr. Greg Stern, Whatcom County health officer.

Measles is a highly contagious respiratory disease that is spread primarily through coughing and sneezing. People who aren't immunized are being urged to get vaccinated, not only to protect themselves but also vulnerable community members such as young children.

In an unrelated incident, public health officials put out a warning on Fri 28 Mar 2014 about a person infected with measles who traveled through Sea-Tac airport while contagious. The California resident likely got measles while traveling in Europe, officials said.

Travelers at Sea-Tac during the following times may have been exposed:

- 8:15 to 10:15 a.m. 21 Mar 2014 in Terminal B;
- 6:30 to 10:00 p.m. 22 Mar 2014 in Terminal B.

People who were exposed and who aren't vaccinated could become sick from 28 Mar 2014 through 12 Apr 2014.

[Byline: Kie Relye]

