[11] Australia (Queensland)
Date: 24 Mar 2014
Source: ABC Australia [edited]
http://www.abc.net.au/news/2014-03-24/3rd-measles-case-confirmed-on-sunshine-coast/5341360


There has been another case of measles on Queensland's Sunshine Coast.

Queensland Health says a person became infectious while visiting Caloundra last week and also visited Stradbroke Island in recent days. It is the 3rd confirmed case on the Sunshine Coast in the past month.

Dr James Smith says, given the large numbers of people potentially exposed to measles, residents in Brisbane and the Sunshine Coast should be on alert. Dr Smith says further measles cases may occur in Brisbane or anywhere in Queensland over the next few weeks.

"If people are adequately vaccinated with 2 recorded doses of measles, mumps and rubella vaccine, they are very unlikely to get the disease," he said. "People who are unsure or have concerns about their immunity to measles should contact their family doctor to check whether they have had both doses of vaccine. True measles is a serious viral infection that causes fever, cough, runny nose, then a red spotty rash and sore eyes a few days later. Symptoms usually start around 7 to 10 days after infection but sometimes longer, so anyone who develops measles-like symptoms within the next fortnight [2 weeks] should contact their GP for advice. It is very important to call the medical practice 1st to say you could have measles, so that staff can take precautions to avoid spreading the disease to others."

Dr Smith says measles can make people very unwell, and although complications are uncommon, they can be serious.

[Byline: Jo Skinner]

